%I A393224 #48 Jun 28 2026 16:41:20
%S A393224 140929,121,43,23,53,43691,174763,277,59,715827883,149,83,431,283,107,
%T A393224 2833
%N A393224 a(n) = gcd_{k >= 1} gcd(A395171(n)^(prime(n)*k) - 1, A395171(n)! - 1).
%C A393224 By definition of A395171, gcd(A395171(n)^(p_n*k) - 1, A395171(n)! - 1) > 1 holds for any integer k >= 1 (where p_n denotes the n-th prime).
%C A393224 The present sequence records the greatest common divisor, over all integers k >= 1, of these values. A395171(11) = 357913941 gives a(11) = 715827883.
%C A393224 Since A395171(18) > 10^8, it follows that a(18) >= 100000007.
%H A393224 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/questions/510302/if-gcdn3-1-n-11-must-it-be-equal-to-140929">If gcd(n^3-1, n!-1)>1, must it be equal to 140929?</a>.
%H A393224 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/questions/510656/can-gcdnk-pm-1-hspace2mm-n-pm-11-have-arbitrarily-many-but-finitel">Can gcd(n^k +- 1, n! +- 1) > 1 have arbitrarily many but finitely many solutions?</a>.
%H A393224 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/q/511242">Answer to: Universal solutions of gcd(n^{p*k}-1, n!-1)>1 for every odd prime p</a>.
%H A393224 Aldo Roberto Pessolano, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20682049">Computational certification of OEIS A395171(11) and bounds for A395171(18)</a>, Zenodo, 2026.
%e A393224 a(2) = 140929 since gcd_{k >= 1} gcd(2283^(3*k) - 1, 2283! - 1) = 140929.
%Y A393224 Cf. A000978, A005384, A395115, A395171, A395286, A395944.
%K A393224 nonn,hard,more,changed
%O A393224 2,1
